It's also possible to return a kind of empty/void checkpoint mark like this:

```
    @Override
    public UnboundedSource.CheckpointMark getCheckpointMark() {
      return new UnboundedSource.CheckpointMark() {
        @Override
        public void finalizeCheckpoint() throws IOException {
          // nothing to do
        }
      };
    }
```
It's a kind of fake checkpoint but better then null IMHO.

Thanks a lot for working on this, @JingsongLi.  

I have one quick initial comment: `FlinkNonSortedCombineRunner` is a (somewhat different) reimplementation of `ReduceFnRunner` with the difference that `ReduceFnRunner` does the merging of windows on the fly, while processing elements, whereas `FlinkNonSortedCombineRunner` does two passes over the input elements, one for determining the merged windows and another one for processing the data which requires materialising all input elements in a list because Flink only allows iterating over the input once.

I think we should either change `FlinkNonSortedCombineRunner` to also only require one pass or reuse `ReduceFnRunner` directly. This is a quick sketch of what that would look like:

```java
public class FlinkMergingNonShuffleReduceFunction<
    K, InputT, AccumT, OutputT, W extends BoundedWindow>
    extends RichGroupReduceFunction<WindowedValue<KV<K, InputT>>, WindowedValue<KV<K, OutputT>>> {

  private final AppliedCombineFn<K, InputT, AccumT, OutputT> combineFn;

  private final WindowingStrategy<Object, W> windowingStrategy;

  private final Map<PCollectionView<?>, WindowingStrategy<?, ?>> sideInputs;

  private final SerializedPipelineOptions serializedOptions;

  public FlinkMergingNonShuffleReduceFunction(
      AppliedCombineFn<K, InputT, AccumT, OutputT> keyedCombineFn,
      WindowingStrategy<Object, W> windowingStrategy,
      Map<PCollectionView<?>, WindowingStrategy<?, ?>> sideInputs,
      PipelineOptions pipelineOptions) {

    this.combineFn = keyedCombineFn;

    this.windowingStrategy = windowingStrategy;
    this.sideInputs = sideInputs;

    this.serializedOptions = new SerializedPipelineOptions(pipelineOptions);

  }

  @Override
  public void reduce(
      Iterable<WindowedValue<KV<K, InputT>>> elements,
      final Collector<WindowedValue<KV<K, OutputT>>> out) throws Exception {

    FlinkSideInputReader sideInputReader =
        new FlinkSideInputReader(sideInputs, getRuntimeContext());

    final Iterator<WindowedValue<KV<K, InputT>>> iterator = elements.iterator();

    // get the first value, we need this for initializing the state internals with the key.
    // we are guaranteed to have a first value, otherwise reduce() would not have been called.
    final WindowedValue<KV<K, InputT>> currentValue = iterator.next();
    final K key = currentValue.getValue().getKey();

    final InMemoryStateInternals<K> stateInternals = InMemoryStateInternals.forKey(key);

    // Used with Batch, we know that all the data is available for this key. We can't use the
    // timer manager from the context because it doesn't exist. So we create one and advance
    // time to the end after processing all elements.
    final InMemoryTimerInternals timerInternals = new InMemoryTimerInternals();
    timerInternals.advanceProcessingTime(Instant.now());
    timerInternals.advanceSynchronizedProcessingTime(Instant.now());

    ReduceFnRunner<K, InputT, OutputT, W> reduceFnRunner = new ReduceFnRunner<>(
        currentValue.getValue().getKey(),
        windowingStrategy,
        ExecutableTriggerStateMachine.create(
            TriggerStateMachines.stateMachineForTrigger(
                Triggers.toProto(windowingStrategy.getTrigger()))),
        stateInternals,
        timerInternals,
        new OutputWindowedValue<KV<K, OutputT>>() {
          @Override
          public void outputWindowedValue(
              KV<K, OutputT> output,
              Instant timestamp,
              Collection<? extends BoundedWindow> windows,
              PaneInfo pane) {
            out.collect(
                WindowedValue.of(output, timestamp, windows, PaneInfo.ON_TIME_AND_ONLY_FIRING));
          }

          @Override
          public <SideOutputT> void sideOutputWindowedValue(
              TupleTag<SideOutputT> tag,
              SideOutputT output,
              Instant timestamp,
              Collection<? extends BoundedWindow> windows,
              PaneInfo pane) {
            throw new UnsupportedOperationException("A ReduceFn cannot use side outputs.");
          }
        },
        sideInputReader,
        null,
        SystemReduceFn.<K, InputT, AccumT, OutputT, W>combining(null, combineFn),
        serializedOptions.getPipelineOptions());

    reduceFnRunner.processElements(new Iterable<WindowedValue<InputT>>() {
      @Override
      public Iterator<WindowedValue<InputT>> iterator() {
        Iterator<WindowedValue<KV<K, InputT>>> concatenated =
            Iterators.concat(Iterators.singletonIterator(currentValue), iterator);
        return Iterators.transform(
            concatenated,
            new Function<WindowedValue<KV<K, InputT>>, WindowedValue<InputT>>() {
              @Nullable
              @Override
              public WindowedValue<InputT> apply(@Nullable WindowedValue<KV<K, InputT>> input) {
                return input.withValue(input.getValue().getValue());
              }
            });
      }
    });

    // Finish any pending windows by advancing the input watermark to infinity.
    timerInternals.advanceInputWatermark(BoundedWindow.TIMESTAMP_MAX_VALUE);

    // Finally, advance the processing time to infinity to fire any timers.
    timerInternals.advanceProcessingTime(BoundedWindow.TIMESTAMP_MAX_VALUE);
    timerInternals.advanceSynchronizedProcessingTime(BoundedWindow.TIMESTAMP_MAX_VALUE);

    fireEligibleTimers(timerInternals, doFnRunner);

  }

}
```

Either of those options seems fine to me. What do you think?
